Finland. He published this story in 1889, and went on to become, in 1919, the first Swiss winner of the Nobel Prize for literature. The Bombardment of Åbo is an ironic Western gaze on life and culture in the Tsarist Empire. Spitteler’s deeply held pacifism breaks through his otherwise sarcastic description of the characters and episodes in the novella.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCrimean War, 1853-1856vFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aBritish warships.  aCrimean War.  aRussia.  acorruption.1 aBirnbaum, Marianna D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpitteler, Carl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2022z978311078048240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789633865743?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633865743423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633865743/original  a978-3-11-078048-2  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK